✅ NFS Setup – MASTER NODE (Server)
1️⃣ Install NFS Kernel Server
sudo apt install nfs-kernel-server -y

2️⃣ Create Shared Directory
sudo mkdir -p /nfs/shared
sudo chmod 777 /nfs/shared

3️⃣ Configure Exports File

Open the exports file:

sudo nano /etc/exports


Add entries for each slave (example IPs from your notes):

/nfs/shared 172.18.181.85(rw,sync,no_subtree_check)
/nfs/shared 172.18.181.86(rw,sync,no_subtree_check)


Save & exit (CTRL + O → ENTER → CTRL + X).

4️⃣ Update Export Table
sudo exportfs -a

5️⃣ Restart NFS Server
sudo systemctl restart nfs-kernel-server

6️⃣ Verify Export
sudo exportfs -v

✅ NFS Setup – SLAVE NODE (Client)
1️⃣ Install NFS Common
sudo apt install nfs-common -y

2️⃣ Create Mount Folder
sudo mkdir -p /nfs/shared

3️⃣ Mount MASTER Shared Directory

Syntax:

sudo mount <master-ip>:/nfs/shared /nfs/shared


Example (from your notes):

sudo mount 172.18.181.85:/nfs/shared /nfs/shared

4️⃣ Test the Mount

Go to directory:

cd /nfs/shared


Create a test file:

touch amrutha.txt


Now check:

ls


You should see amrutha.txt — it will also appear on MASTER.